напиши RecalulateHeight

In the function `ReCalculateHeight`, you'll traverse the tree in a post-order manner (left child, right child, then the node itself) to update each node's height. To calculate the height of a node, you need to look at the heights of its left and right children, take the larger one, and then add one.

Here's an implementation for `ReCalculateHeight`:

```cpp
#include <algorithm> // for std::max

// Helper function to get the height of a node, handling null pointers.
int height(Node* node) {
  if (node == nullptr) {
    return 0; // The height of a non-existent node is 0.
  }
  return node->height;
}

// The main `ReCalculateHeight` function which updates the height of each node.
Node* ReCalculateHeight(Node* root) {
  if (root == nullptr) {
    return nullptr; // If the node is null, just return null.
  }

  // First, calculate the height of the left and right subtrees.
  root->left = ReCalculateHeight(root->left);
  root->right = ReCalculateHeight(root->right);

  // Then, update the height of the current node. The height is the max height of
  // the two children, plus 1 for the current node's level.
  root->height = 1 + std::max(height(root->left), height(root->right));

  return root; // Return the node after its height has been updated.
}
```

Remember, the `height` function is a helper that returns the height of the node and handles null pointers by returning `0`. `ReCalculateHeight` then takes care of the recursive traversal and height updates.

