The segmentation fault you're encountering is due to attempting to access or modify a null pointer in your `BuildTree` function. You must create a new `Node` before you start setting its data and children, but your current check `if (root == nullptr)` does not make sense because you need to allocate memory for a new node first. Moreover, your `main` function does not initialize `root` before passing it to `BuildTree`.

Here's a revised version of the `BuildTree` function:

```cpp
Node* BuildTree(NedoNode arr[], int index, int n) {
  if (index < 0 || index >= n) {
    return nullptr;
  }

  Node* node = new Node;
  node->data = arr[index].data;
  node->left = BuildTree(arr, arr[index].left, n);
  node->right = BuildTree(arr, arr[index].right, n);
  node->height = 1 + std::max(height(node->left), height(node->right));

  return node;
}
```

